				 Local stalwarts earn BCG praise
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Dec. 3: The Tata group, Infosys, Mahindra amp; Mahindra, Wipro and Ranbaxy are among the 20 Indian companies that have the potential to challenge big players such as General Electric and Wal-Mart.																								According to Boston Consulting Groups latest report, titled 2008 Global Challengers, these 20 firms belong to an elite list of the 100 most formidable international companies that could reshape global industries. 																								China, Russia, Brazil and Mexico also have some of the fastest-growing companies in the world.																								The group of 100 has a combined annual revenue of $1.2 trillion and is growing at an average rate of more than 20 per cent a year. The 20 Indian companies have a cumulative annual revenue of $3.9 billion for 2006 and they have an impressive growth rate of 31 per cent from 2004 to 2006.																								Industry leaders need to understand these new rivals and act quickly, David Michael, the reports co-author, said in a statement. For those who move fast, the challengers could become key clients, suppliers, and even strategic partners. For those who dont, the challengers will represent fierce competition and, in time, become potential acquirers, he added.																								According to Hal Sirkin, senior vice-president with BCG and co-author of the report, the leader from India is the Tata group. 
